visuals.title: Colony
visuals.description:
This started as a random space filing algorithm, then I changed the circles for lines drawn out from the centre of the circle by a tweaked version of Jared Tarbell's sand painter algorithm from http://www.complexification.net/gallery/

The paint algorithm was then tweaked to allow it to draw outside the bounds of the circle because it looks nice.

Note this will tie up your browser until its painted 8000 'Colonies' which can take a while.

visuals.title: Twk: Colony
visuals.description: Tweaked to stop at > 6000 circles' and avoid some of processing.js' less efficient bits of coding. Runs a fair bit slower in Firefox 23, around 70% slower, than in Chrome or Safari on my old 32bit iMac, YMMV.

visuals.title: Circulate
visuals.description: Controls: Mouse pressed stops the lines from spiraling inward, and stops showing their paths. Mouse not pressed sends the lines spiraling inward. At first let the mouse hold still in the center for a few seconds, then start. Also try holding down the mouse and moving it around the screen a bit, and then releasing the mouse and hold it perfectly still, watching what happens. The code is relatively easy to figure out, it's a particle system. Enjoy.

visuals.title: Project_Schwartzberg
visuals.description: Comets are small bodies orbiting the Sun. They are made up of easily evaporated ices. When one approaches the sun, it forms an atmosphere around its nucleus, called a coma (that is what "glows"). The dust and gas in the coma form two tails (1 of Ionized molecules/gas and 1 of dust). Therefore, tails of a comet are only formed when a comet is close to the sun. Also, as the comet gets closer the the sun, the tails get longer. Halley's comet in particular takes about 76 years to make a full revolution, and will be seen again in 2062, and was last seen in 1986.
visuals.instructions: Read all of the instructions within the program!

visuals.title: Moving Blue Mountains
visuals.description:
Edited to add horizontal motion, added minor tweaks to make it hold good framerate.

Had to remove the fade and clouds to make it run smooth, I am really sorry to the original author.

A mountain range landscape.

Inspired by lesson 38 of Fun Programming: http://funprogramming.org/38-Animate-the-ocean-surface-using-noise.html 

Colors chosen to work on Javascript (the clouds and the sky gradient look different on Java mode). Also, I don't know why, the lerpColor didn't work on Java, it's possible to get the same effect with separated map functions for hue, saturation and brightness though.
visuals.instructions:
Mouse click to generate a new pattern.
Press s to save as an image.

visuals.title: happyPlace
visuals.description:
Happy Place renders the resulting configuration of a system of friendly nodes. They are connected at random with preferences to nodes closer. Connections between nodes are considered friendships.  Nodes position themselves with only two goals in mind: 
A. Move close to friends but no closer than some minimum distance.
B. Distance self from non-friends as reasonably as possible.   (Ported from Jared Tarbell at complexification.net)

visuals.title: FinalProject_BHammam
visuals.description: This is modeling the phenomenon that is the electromagnetic (EM) spectrum. The EM spectrum is different wavelengths of radiation, the colors represent the wavelengths as pertaining to visible light. Colors such as violet have shorter wavelengths, whereas colors like red have longer wavelengths. The red and blueshift are caused by something called the Dopler Effect, basically, when planets are moving away from us they appear to have a red tint because the wavelengths elongate as they come towards us, the planets that are moving towards us appear to be blue.
visuals.instructions: Move the mouse to see different levels of the EM spectrum, press a key to see the redshift. Click the mouse to see blueshift. see description for explanation of the EM spectrum, redshift, and blueshift.

visuals.title: Obj viewer
visuals.description:
Reads data from an obj format and displays it.

An obj format is a generic format used by most 3d software packages to describe a mesh. In fact, this model was exported out from Maya.

There's so much more to be done with this, but here's a start!

Controls:
    - Drag left-click to rotate camera.
    - Drag middle-click to move camera.
    - Drag right-click to zoom.
    - E to toggle edges.
    - P to toggle points.
    - F to toggle faces.

visuals.title: USphHarmonics01
visuals.description:
Simple implementation of the well-known series of wave functions known as spherical harmonics, which are defined in spherical coordinates and thus define 3D volumes. 

This sketch demonstrates a possible way to morph between  two UGeometry geometries, provided that the two objects have the same number of faces.

Written using Paul Bourke's code as a reference:
http://paulbourke.net/geometry/sphericalh/

(Part of my series of reference implementations of classic algorithms...)

visuals.title: Kinect 3D scanner
visuals.description:
Simple 3D scanner using the Kinect.

Doesn't work in the browser. You need a Kinect to run it and the controlP5 (version controlP5_1.5.1), hemesh and simple-openni libraries installed. 
 
Select the scanner area with the controls and press the "take scan" button to capture the 3D points inside the box. A mesh is created with the Hemesh library and saved in the sketch directory. The colors of the mesh faces are saved in a different file. Press the "take scan" button again to take more scans. 
 
Use http://www.openprocessing.org/sketch/62533 to read and represent the mesh.

b - Increases the blue value

- RETURN/ENTER/CTRL = confirm your seed and generate signature
- ALT = save image

visuals.title: Pixel Level Collision Detection
visuals.description:
The bigger fish follows the mouse position.

In this sketch the two fish only collide when two non-transparent pixels (one from each image) appear at the same screen position.

When a collision occurs the sketch draws a red box round each image. 

The algorithm is quite efficient because it first tests to see if the images overlap, and if they do it then compares only those pixels in the overlap area are tested.

visuals.title: Diversity
visuals.description: 色々な感情や個性を表すのに丸を動かすだけでは物足りないと思ったので、四角と三角を入れました。特に三角を大きくしたのは私たち十代の心は自我が成長して大人になりきれないギザギザした気持ちを表すためでもあります。

visuals.title: 私のただ一つの望み
visuals.description: まず、何かに反応するという課題の項目を満たせる作品を考えるのに時間を要しました。カメラにするかマウスにするかでも悩みましたが、カメラにするにしてもあまり発想がうかばなかったのでマウスにする方を選びました。次に、他の人の作品をいっぱい見て、図形のものが多かったので文字だったらかぶらないのではと考えました。ただ文字を表示するだけでは面白くなく、課題のマウスに反応するという項目が満たせません。その為、マウスを近づけたら文字がバラバラになるようにしました。ただのフォントだったら工夫が足りないのでそこは自分で探し、はんなりフォントを取り入れました。フォントを読み込む方法がわからなかったのでコードはネットにあったものを、ファイルは先生に協力してもらい入れることができました。書く文字はすぐに決まりました。この作品は、欲望はあっけなくバラバラに壊されるものだがしぶとく願い続けられるものだということを示唆しております。

visuals.title: Psychedelic Noise 5 - B&W
visuals.description:
Just playing with noise.

Mouse click to generate a new seamless pattern
Press any key to save it

It is similar to an old sketch of mine (http://www.openprocessing.org/sketch/187650) but with some important differences:

* I've played with noiseDetail this time to make the curves smoother

* I've used a different strategy to make the color transitions smooth

* I've used the equation of the torus to make the pattern seamless

visuals.title: Pulsating pixels
visuals.description: Each pixel is pulsating from white to black based on mapping sin() function. The speed of oscilation, however, varies for different pixels (like z = 5 + sinx*siny), which creates progressively smaler "waves". As the waves' length becomes less then a pixel, complex patterns start emerging (let it run for long enough).

  - Press any key to save the canvas to a jpg.

visuals.title: Random palette generator
visuals.description:
A tweak of my last sketch in which I used random colors, but selected random limits in order to get something not too random, with colors that go well together.

It resulted in some interesting palettes so I decided to do something that allows me to see which values produce these colors and experiment with different values.

Mouse over the pattern will show the red, green and blue parameters of the color.
Mouse click over the pattern will load a new one with the same rule.
Click on Random to reload with random rules.
Click on Run to reload with the rules selected with the sliders.

visuals.title: Fractal 909-Oscillating Rectangles
visuals.description:
The idea: Start with a rectangle, and divide it in two - draw a line to mark the boundary. Now animate it: oscillate that line, and the proportions, back and forth. Now, recurse down into the two child rectangles, oscillating faster for more-nested rectangles.

Controls: move the mouse up & down to damp the oscillation. Press a key to change the render: instead of drawing lines, draw a dot at the center of where the lines would be.

visuals.title: Lindenmayer Plants
visuals.description:
Finally had some time to extend my old l-system project. Check tutorial for general explanations: http://paulbourke.net/fractals/lsys/. This time most replacement rules consist of sets of possible replacements which are chosen randomly within a given likelihood. The axiom and the replacements (with their likelihoods) are written on the bottom of the drawing:

Controls:
Click with mouse = new random plant
Space = same plant with new random values
Left/ Right Arrow = increase / decrease angle
Plus / Minus = add / remove  iteration (don't add too much iterations)
t = show / hide text

visuals.title: Catch That Arial
visuals.description:
Arial and Helvetica are two typefaces that you cannot escape from in this modern life. If you pay (maybe just a little bit) attention to fonts, I guess this has occurs to you: Is that text in Arial or Helvetica?

Indeed, they are very similar but still there are some clues to find. Click ↓and try to catch the Arial among the Helvetica-s!

visuals.title: Rorschach Generator
visuals.description:
To see how this works, hit 'f' to disable the filter. You'll see that the balls are darkest at the center and lightest at the outside. The filter gets rid of everything lighter than the threshold, and turns everything else black. 


controls:
Various modes of motion: 1-7
Reset everything: z
Toggle Rorschach mode: r
Cycle through shapes: s
Invert shape: i
Invert colors toggle: b
Random/BW color switch: c
Pause motion: p
Filter toggle: f
Discrete/Continuous: d

Change number of balls: _,+
Change radius: -,=
Change discretization steps: {,}
Adjust threshold: [,]

visuals.title: Noise flow field painter
visuals.description:
*It may need a moment to load*

Paints an image with strokes that are rotated by a flow field driven from noise.

If you want to try it on your own image you need to drag and drop an image in the sketch's files tab. Then add your image's file name to the variable imgNames (it's near the top). It doesn't capture details very well so close ups work best.

Controls:
  - Click to change to the next image.
  - Press any key to save the canvas to a jpg.
visuals.instructions: Click for the next image, press a key to save a jpg.

visuals.title: Maze Generator: Randomized Kruskal's Algorithm
visuals.description:
Another maze generation program. This is one is a lot less fun than the last one but the code is a lot tidier and there is now a working solver. 

For more resources on Kruskal's algorithm, see:
* http://weblog.jamisbuck.org/2011/1/3/maze-generation-kruskal-s-algorithm
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maze_generation_algorithm#Randomized_Kruskal's_algorithm
Basically, it puts the cells into sets, which are all merged (by removing a wall between them) until all the cells are connected. The colors you see are the sets.

Kruskal's algorithm generates perfect mazes with a uniform spanning tree.
visuals.instructions: Use the controls on the right. See description for more info.

visuals.title: 苦痛の団子
visuals.description:
この作品を作るのはとても大変でしたが、コーディングの理解が深くなったと思うので、スキルの一つとして習えてとても良かったと思います。
この作品で工夫した点は団子に顔をつけたこと、そして色がいいスピードで変わるようにしたことです。団子に顔をつけるのは大体全て、同じ配置になるようにしたり、アーチという新しい形を何度も打ち直して作ったりすることで他とは違う新しい顔ができたように感じます。団子の色が変わるのも、とてもチカチカしていたのをいいスピードに直すことで、みてて面白いものになったかなと思います。また、自分の欲しい色を桜や串に活用できたことも自分のイメージともっとつながりました。
苦労した点はたくさんあります。花弁の形がないので、丸で代用したり、セーブせずにタブを消して１からやり直したり、顔が２個だけに現れたり、アーチの形がうまくいかなかったり。間違っていると出てくる所は別に間違いがあることで全体的にコードが動かなかったり、試行錯誤の繰り返しでした。特に顔の配置や団子を一致させて動かさせることに苦労しました。
しかし、消した後もまたできたことで自分でまた練習ができて、理解がより深まり、大変でしたが、全体的に練習ができて良かったと思います。色々ありましたが、楽しんで作ることができました。

visuals.title: 音符のコンサート〜
visuals.description: タイトル通り音符たちのコンサートをイメージして作った作品です。工夫できたと思う点は、それぞれ音楽のスタイルがあってそのスタイルと音符自体の特徴をできるだけ合わせようとした点と音楽が止まった時に一緒に出てくる紙吹雪をイメージした四角です。苦労した点は、音楽が鳴らなかったり、音符の色が反対になったりとはっきりと問題が何か示されないことで試行錯誤が多かったことです。また、やりこととどれだけ時間があるのか、どれだけできるのかなど決めたり、判断したり、コードをネットで探して試してみたりするのも難しかったです。まだ、改善したい部分はありますが、今回もたくさんのことが学べました。

visuals.title: Mind and Body are one and the same
visuals.description:
System of neurons grow within brightness zones of an image, displaying the underlying color.

controls:
mouse press- add new neural system, seeking a brighter region from the previous.
k - kill the oldest system. VERY useful to speed up during later stages!
l - add new neural system seeking the darkest region
h- add new neural system seeking the brightest region


The picture driving the growth is a paint of Baruch Spinoza.
Spinoza had a radical solution to the mind body problem: the mind and body are are just two aspects of one same thing.
This code is a visual metaphor for his conception.

visuals.title: Draw generative neurons using Poisson process
visuals.description:
A lthough a neuron's firing rate is often communicated as regularly spaced events which occur at a changing rate, this is a convenient oversimplification. In computational neuroscience, the timing of individual action potentials  is  often described mathematically as an inhomogenous Poisson process - wherein the time between subsequent firing events follow an exponential frequency distribution.
In this graphic, I attempt to capture this statistical irregularity, by drawing each neuron according to a Poisson process.

visuals.title: Circulate
visuals.description: Controls: Mouse pressed stops the lines from spiraling inward, and stops showing their paths. Mouse not pressed sends the lines spiraling inward. At first let the mouse hold still in the center for a few seconds, then start. Also try holding down the mouse and moving it around the screen a bit, and then releasing the mouse and hold it perfectly still, watching what happens. The code is relatively easy to figure out, it's a particle system. Enjoy.

visuals.title: Noise flow field painter
visuals.description:
*It may need a moment to load*

Paints an image with strokes that are rotated by a flow field driven from noise.

If you want to try it on your own image you need to drag and drop an image in the sketch's files tab. Then add your image's file name to the variable imgNames (it's near the top). It doesn't capture details very well so close ups work best.

Controls:
  - Click to change to the next image.
  - Press any key to save the canvas to a jpg.
visuals.instructions: Click for the next image, press a key to save a jpg.

visuals.title: abstract01js
visuals.description:
abstract01js is a reworking of an old 2D Processing sketch from 2003, created for for the exhibition Abstraction Now in Vienna.

The 2010 version was recreated using Processing.js for  Aram Bartholl's "Speed Show 4: Super Niche" http://fffff.at/speed-show-4/using Processing.js. It was later featured by Processingjs.org for the 1.0 release.

Another version can be seen here:
http://mariuswatz.com/works/abstract01js/

visuals.title: Force Directed Placement
visuals.description:
A graph is drawn considering the edges like springs and the  nodes like masses.

the key controls are:
't' - toggle trail rendering
'b' - toggle masses rendering
'+' - add masses
any other key to switch between random generation and fully connected graph.
click with the mouse to have some fun.

in RANDOM mode every mass increase as new masses are created and connected with it.
in GRAPH mode every node has the same mass to let the algorithm converge to a beautiful star shape.

comments.text:
Hi Elisabeth, I am part of a small startup in Tucson, Arizona, that makes audio visualization softwares. I am a big fan of your sketches on open processing and was wondering if we could chat about making audio visualization sketches and getting your input! My email is danielrhim@gmail.com. I hope that we can chat soon. 

Daniel
This is really well done, great work!
it is out of this world
Add noStroke(); to make it more smooth
it looks like a tree growing!
